Ben Collier

Addition of Determination and Collection Object diagrams

1      Overview

The Detailed Conceptual Model (DCM) is a series of documents showing entities, their relationships and relevant attributes of both for each model diagram. The entities and relationships are built on the High-Level Conceptual Model (H-LCM: Data Architecture Requirements Appendix A.doc), with inputs from:

1.1   EMu

This existing CMS solution at The Museum. We have taken a full data dictionary of the database and combined this with field usage statistics, to update the model and provide mappings from EMu to this DCLM. This helps us ensure we have full coverage of the existing CMSs data requirements. The EMu data dictionary it split into modules, and this model will show which modules and field apply to which entities and attributes. The RECODE EMu DataDictionary Mappings list is the reference, showing the detailed mappings from EMu to the data model.

1.2   Functional Requirements

Information based around stakeholder definitions of what the new CMS will need to provide. These documents are available to bidders and the DCM addresses each the User Story and Data Element and defines a modelling solution to support them. The DCM shows the outcome of this process, with the mappings in a separate document.  

1.3   External schemas and standards

The DCM will put its objects into context, showing where they reference external standards (e.g. SPECTRUM from the Collections Trust) and schemas (e.g. Darwin Code from the Biodiversity Information Standards). The DCM shows where its objects and attributes are analogous to the external ones and explains any differences and complexities. 

1.4   Results 

These sources have led to: 

Additions and changes to the entities and relationships from the H-LCM, as the requirements are more complex 

The additions of attributes and attribute groups to the entities and relationships 

The aim is to give readers a full representation of The Museums interpretation of its collection data model, showing how it links to the relevant concepts from a variety of sources. This should give suppliers enough information to assess how the Museums data model could be implemented in their proposed solution and be the starting point for detailed discussions in the latter stages of the procurement process. 

2      Location

2.1   Location Summary

The location describes where objects within the collection are physically located. This may encompass:

         storage locations (including freezers)

         display locations

         offices and labs

         external locations (e.g. for touring exhibitions)

2.2   Related EMu Concepts

This diagram addresses the details of the elocations and emovements modules:

2.2.1  elocations

This Records storage and display locations within an institution, e.g. building, floor, room, cabinet, shelf, box. In addition to recording the location hierarchy, it captures physical attributes of that location e.g. dimensions.  X-Y-Z co-ordinates are used for spatial analysis of pest trap data using the mapper interface. All these properties are addressed here. Move requests and location history are also handled in this module and addressed in this diagram.

More work is needed for location condition checking and reporting requirements.

2.2.2  emovements

This records movements of collection items into and out of an institution. The core data for this module is addressed here, but some fields may be addressed within processes that specifically manage the processes that instigate moves into an out of the Museum (e.g. Loans).

2.2.3  Data Cleansing Areas

This section highlights potential areas that may need to be considered when mapping and cleansing the existing data. These are limited to points noticed in initial explorations of the EMu data and aren't intended to be exhaustive.

         Locations should be a strict hierarchy, and duplicates should be removed

         Indexing Details there are Collection Names (e.g. Crustacea) that seem to be above taxonomic Order, so appear to break the indexing details hierarchy. And there are many that appear to have no child locations. We also need to understand how the indexing is used and how it correlates to the levels physical location hierarchy.

         Location Type should be rationalised

2.3   User Stories

The "Data Model" column in the RECODE User Stories list has the relevant information under the Process, LMC - Location and Movement Control, with the Data Model values showing how the Goal is addressed by the data model.

The outcomes of these are in this diagram, but without explicit links.

2.4   External References

The specific links to this diagrams entities and attributes fully linked in the Standards Review.xlsx document. This diagram has incorporated them but leaves out the full list of detailed references for conciseness.

2.4.1  CIDOC-CRM (CIDOC):

https://www.cidoc-crm.org/

The Location Unit:

https://cidoc-crm.org/FunctionalUnits/location-information shows how locations are handled in the CIDOC-CRM data model. One key difference is that this diagram does not have a separate "move" entity, linking objects to locations, but records the relevant information in the relationships between locations, and between objects and locations, to show different types of location and location histories. A MoveRequest links relevant records together, along with data about requests to move objects or moveable locations.

2.4.2  SPECTRUM (Collections Trust):

https://collectionstrust.org.uk/spectrum/spectrum-5/

Spectrum has the procedure units of information we need to reference here https://collectionstrust.org.uk/resource/location-and-movement-control-suggested-procedure/, these are included in this diagram, with full references in the standards review. Location condition note might need more expansion - cf Related EMu Concepts

2.5   Data Model

Location is where a CollectionObject is stored. This represents a hierarchy from site and building level down to granular containers such as a drawer or box.

There are multiple ways that Locations and CollectionObject s can be linked, and these are modelled using Type and Status in the ObjectLocation and LocationLocation entities. This allows different types of relationships to be described and to show movement histories.

2.5.1  Location

Name

Location

Definition

A Location is a position in a hierarchy of places where an object may be situated at a given time.

Scope

A Location may contain data about its type, and a link to a parent Location.

Context

A Location can be the normal location of a CollectionObject and, in addition to storage units, can include display cases, galleries, and laboratories; a location type attribute will be included to reflect these. Locations can be moveable (e.g. drawers, boxes and other containers), they still fit in this model so long as the parent is changed when one is moved.

A history of all locations at which objects are, or have been, located is retained for all objects, as well as locations reserved for objects that may be temporarily elsewhere (e.g. in an exhibition).

The building level Location should have an Address.

There will need to be access controls to the data as some locations are sensitive.

External References

CIDOC:

              This is a synonym of E53 Place.

              P87 is identified by links a place to a place appellation, and an address is a subtype of this.

Notes

we might need to have location values of "not in place" and "on loan" to show what we know about a location when it cannot be accurately defined

2.5.2  LocationLocation

Name

LocationLocation

Definition

A LocationLocation is the link between two Locations either current, past or proposed.

Scope

 

Context

LocationLocations are used to maintain CollectionObjects' movement histories, along with ObjectLocations.

There may be data linking the LocationLocation to an external Health & Safety system for risk assessments for moves.

External References

CIDOC:

       This is a has the details for P88 consists of and P89 falls within.

       The relationship for Location moves are: P26 moved to; P27 moved from.

Notes

from Spectrum "You have appropriate insurance or indemnity cover in place before transporting objects, particularly in the case of borrowed objects."

2.5.2.1.2      Position

Name

Position

Type

 

Definition

A Location may have a specific position within its parent Location.

Scope

 

Context

 

Examples

         Some parent Locations have ordered positions for their children (e.g. cabinet with drawers) the ordering is a property or the link between the parent and child. It will be constrained by the attributes of the parent (e.g. a drawer cannot be in position 9 of an 8-slot cabinet)

         Can also have coordinates or other description within a parent Location.

         Position of a cabinet in a room

         A room might be on the North side of a building's floor

External References

         E47 Spatial Coordinates.

2.5.3  ObjectLocation

Name

ObjectLocation

Definition

An ObjectLocation is the link between a CollectionObject and one of its current, past or proposed Locations

Scope

A CollectionObject's location history will be informed by the ObjectLocation.

Context

 

Examples

There may be data linking the ObjectLocation to an external Health & Safety system for risk assessments.

External References

CIDOC:

The following relate E18 Physical Thing and E19 Physical Object to E53 Place and are addressed here:

         P59 has section

         P53 has former or current location

         P55 has a current location

         P54 has current permanent location

A move is a modelled as a change of Location for a CollectionObject, with two ObjectLocations, so both the Entity, E9 Move and the properties

         P26 moved to

         P27 moved from

         P25 moved

are modelled in this entity and it relationships with CollectionObject and Location.

         P25 moved has the E19 Physical Object (CollectionObject) as the passive participant of the E9 Move (ObjectLocation)

         P26 moved to and P27 moved from are the relationships between two ObjectLocations and the CollectionObject's new and old Locations

Notes

3      Determination

3.1   Summary

Determinations apply taxonomic terms to IdentifiableItems. This model allows us to maintain a history of Determinations for each IdentifiableItem.

Each specimen can have a history of identifications and an identification can apply to many specimens. Determination is used to resolve and enhance this many-to-many relationship.

3.2   Related EMu Concepts

EMu uses the eCatalogue module to store the determination data and link to eTaxonomy

3.2.1  eCatalogue

Records information about each item in the collection. This is the main module and heart of EMu and is typically tailored to an institution.

3.2.2  eTaxonomy

Stores nomenclature (systematic taxonomic names).

3.3   User Stories

3.4   External References

3.4.1  Darwin Core

https://dwc.tdwg.org/list/#dwc_Identification A taxonomic determination (e.g., the assignment to a taxon).

3.5   Data Model

Determinations link IdentifiableItems to Classifications. Part of creating an IdentifiableItem is making a determination of its classification.

Any object in the museum can have multiple competing determinations, which need to be evidenced and recorded.

The different Classification schemes are modelled using the same entities.

3.5.1  Determination

Name

Determination

Definition

A Determination is an opinion that an IdentifiableItem is of a particular Classification. It links the relevant information that supports the determination.

Scope

A Determination may contain data about:

         (link to) Taxonomic term, in Classification

         Name of the Determiner(s)

         Date of determination

         Basis of the Determination

Context

This would also record the history. IdentifiableItems can be reidentified, and this will lead to new Determination records. The previous ones may be updated to unaccepted, but this does not imply that they were wrong.

dwc:previousIdentifications

4      Collection Object

4.1   Summary

The collection object concept is central to the CMS data model. This broadly represents a physical object that is part of, or is being brought into, the Museums collection and/or custody, and is subject to the many processes involved in collections management and cataloguing.

Information will be attached to a collection object to reflect where, when and by whom it was collected, who is responsible for its care within the collection, where it is (and has been) stored within the Museum, and what its scientific classification and stratigraphic origin is. In addition to this, there is a whole extra wealth of detailed data that is not represented at the level of detail in the conceptual model.

The most significant modelling challenge however is that in the real world, a collection object is not a simple definition. While some examples are relatively straightforward, such as an individual insect mounted on a pin, many examples are more complex. Examples include:

         a number of different organisms stored and handled together, such as a jar of frogs

         a single organism with parts that have been separated and are stored in different locations, such as a skeleton made up of multiple bones

         an unsorted lot of material that may belong to a number of organisms, such as the contents of an insect trap

         a single physical object that may contain a number of different components that are classified independently, such as a rock slab containing multiple fossilised organisms

         an object which has produced derivative objects, such as an insect which has had a leg removed for analysis

         an object which has had samples taken for DNA analysis, such as a section taken from a dried leaf on a herbarium sheet

         an object which represents organisms from multiple disciplines, such as a gall (entomology) on a leaf (botany)

         two objects that may have been collected together and represent a real-world relationship, such as a host-parasite relationship represented by a louse that was found on a bird specimen

The impact of this is that:

1.       a collection object in the data will not always represent just a single object in the physical world.

2.       there are a range of complex relationships that need to be maintained between objects, groups of objects, and their various components, derivatives and samples

3.       each of these examples may be subject together or independently to the various collections management and cataloguing processes

4.       relationships must be maintained and updated over time to retain provenance information, as processes cause objects to be created, split, merged and destroyed

5.       the need to apportion scientific classifications to these adds complexity for example, a curator or researcher needs to know whether multiple objects (e.g. bones or DNA samples) originate from the same individual of a particular species

For these reasons, the collection object cannot be represented by just a single simple entity in the data model.

4.2   Related EMu Concepts

4.2.1  eCatalogue

4.3   User Stories

4.4   External References

4.5   Data Model

CollectionObject and IdentifiableItem can be used to represent different properties of what can be the same physical thing.

All the links to the Collection Object are shown in the Overview, but many are missing from this diagram for clarity. Each relationship an entity that has with the Collection Object entities is described on those entities' diagrams.

Concepts to Consider:

         Object: Anything considered and object will be a CollectionObject in this model.

         Lot: Any group of objects that will not be physically separated (10 fish in a jar) will be a single CollectionObject. Unsorted material could be a CollectionObject, linked to a single IdentifiableItem, or CollectedMaterial.

         Acquisition lot: The Acquisition will group these. There may be a need for an AcquiredMaterial entity (though this might be pre-acquisition!)

         Sample: This will be another CollectionObject, with data in the RelationshipType on its creation.

         Bulk sample:  This will be CollectedMaterial.

         Specimen: Anything fitting the wide definition of specimen will probably be a CollectionObject.

         Multi-specimen object: This will be a single CollectionObject, with multiple linked IdentifiableItems.

         Multi-part object: This will be linked CollectionObjects, with data in the RelationshipTypes, linking to a single IdentifiableItem.

         Material: Covered by objects, lots, samples and bulk samples.

         Derived object: This is a CollectionObject, that is a child of another - the RelationshipType will define it as derived

         Digital object: This will be a CollectionObject, with a flag to indicate there is no physical object in the collection. The digital version might be in the CMS, or linked to (e.g. PID)

         Determination: This is show in the Determination entity.

         Preparation: This is a derived object, so a CollectionObject. details of how it was prepared from its parent will be in the RelationshipType.

4.5.1  Collection Object

Name

CollectionObject

Definition

This is a representation of an item that will be physically handled, loaned or moved in collection moves.

Scope

A CollectionObject may link to one or more IdentifiableItems that equate to one or more taxa that are present in the CollectionObject. As well as the specimen(s) or sample(s), the CollectionObject also includes any physical media used to preserve and present them, such as a microscope slide, herbarium sheet or jar.

Context

A CollectionObject can have further CollectionObjects derived from it.

Examples

         This simplest case is one CollectionObject and one IdentifiableItem which describe different attributes of the are the same physical object (for example, a single insect on a pin).

         When we have a parasite on the insect, we have two different species and so two IdentifiableItems that are not separate collection objects.

         One large IdentifiableItem, e.g. a large skeleton can have components stored in multiple locations simultaneously, so will be represented by multiple related CollectionObjects.

External References

CIDOC:

         This is an E19 Physical Object.

DwC

         A dwc:FossilSpecimen maps exactly to a CollectionObject.

4.5.1.2.3      To ObjectGroup

To entity

ObjectGroup

From cardinality

0..*

To cardinality

0..*

Label

may be included in or be representation of

Notes

ObjectGroups can contain specimens that have CollectionObject records. Care will have to be taken to ensure attributes are aggregated accurately: either by duplicating CollectionObject attributes in ObjectGroup's attributes, or ensuring they are excluded and the CollectionObject's attributes are included in any aggregations.

A CollectionObject can also be used a proxy for an ObjectGroup in any transactions that an entire ObjectGroup could be involved in.

4.5.2  Identifiable Item

Name

IdentifiableItem

Definition

This represents a physical instance in the collection of a single specific taxon. It may correspond to a single CollectionObject, be spread across multiple CollectionObjects, or represent part of a CollectionObject.

Scope

What that taxon is might be not fully known, or there may be different opinions from different people over time, so we allow for multiple Determinations with citations.

Context

Could be a representation of a physical instance. e.g. for a model

4.5.3  Composition

Name

Composition

Definition

This describes the relationship between CollectionObjects and IdentifiableItems

Scope

This defines how multiple species can be present on a single CollectionObject, or how multiple CollectionObjects can link to a single IdentifiableItem.

Context

This could be used to define how to display data about the specimen.

External References

Darwin Core:

dwc:relatedResourceID

Notes

Examples:

         The link between an insect on a pin and its identification

         Where specimens are on a herbarium sheet or sheets

         Where minerals are in a rock sample

         The link between different parts of an animal and its identification

4.5.4  Object Relationship

Name

ObjectRelationship

Definition

This describes the event of how different CollectionObjects came to be related to each other

Scope

New child CollectionObjects are created in situations such as:

         a specimen is split for analysis.

         an item on display is taken apart for storage.

         A new organism is bred or grown

A new parent CollectionObject are created when items are combined from different StorageLocations into a single item. e.g. a bound volume of herbarium sheet is made.

Context

There may also be other relationships between CollectionObjects , e.g. synecology, the relationship between different taxa collected at the Locality (prey, feeding etc)

External References

Darwin Core:

dwc:relatedResourceID

dwc:associatedSequences

4.5.6  Agent Role

Name

AgentRole

Definition

This is an activity an Agent participates in as a custodian of a CollectionObject.

Scope

It may contain data about long term responsibility of a CollectionObject. It could also contain data about changes to the curation of an object.

Context

Multiple Agents can be associated with a single AgentRole, but some activities can only have one related Agent.

External References

This is the based on the Activity in the PROV 3-axiom schema. (with the CollectionObject being the used Entity and the Agent the wasAssociatedWith Agent)

5      Agent

5.1   Summary

Agent is a generic term that is used to cover people, organisations, groups, and software agents in the context of the data model.

This has been put in a model with now top-level subtypes. When these are used in diagrams the association will describe the subtype of Agent represented, e.g. Agent::Person [1..*] -may curate- CollectionObject [0..*].

5.2   Related EMu Concepts

This diagram addresses the details of the eparties module:

5.2.1  Eparties

This, "Records details about people and organisations with a relationship with an institution and its collection.". It is a flat structure with some associated nested tables containing linked data.

 

5.3   User Stories

The RECODE User Stories list for the Process, CAT_PAR - PARTIES, with the Data Model values showing how the Goal is addressed by the data model.

The outcomes of these are in this diagram, but without explicit links.

5.4   External References

The specific links to this diagrams entities and attributes fully linked in the Standards Review.xlsx document. This diagram has incorporated them but leaves out the full list of detailed references for conciseness.

5.4.1  CIDOC-CRM (CIDOC)

Person Nationality Information. This links E21 Person to a E67 Birth event which occurred at a E53 Place. It also shows how a E21 can be a current or former member of a E74 Group and have a E55 Type.

Institution Information. This shows that a E74 Group can be a E40 Legal Body and can be both a subtype of and/or comprised of E39 Actors. This implies that a E74 can contain other E74s. The Group as an E39 Actor represents and Institution, which may have

Group Dynamics.

5.4.2  SPECTRUM (Collections Trust)

Spectrum does not have specific processes for the entering and maintaining party data. It does have processes for where people and organisations should be involved in its processes and these will be addressed in the relevant diagram

5.5   Data Model

Agent has relationships with many other entities, these are not shown here for clarity - CollectionObject is linked to here as an example. Agent relationships are included on other diagrams, with their context.

5.5.1  Agent

Name

Agent

Definition

An Agent is a named Person, Organisation, Group or SoftwareAgent.

Scope

An Agent may contain data that uniquely identifies it, and makes it clear to any user who or what they are.

Context

The subtypes will have different attributes, e.g. a Person will have a first, last and other names, DoB & DoD. An Organisation will have a type and an address.

There may be a requirement to anonymise some values certain records for some groups of users.

Notes

Collection, as a type of group?
